Doc;<br><br>
You mentioned Winter Soldiers. The only Winter Soldiers (Marines) I agree with are those I know who like to go Lion hunting in the snow.  I cannot stand a bunch of wailing souls who regret having fought in a just war. The Ron Kovic type who bends every which way the wind blows. There are many to whom the media has drawn public attention toward who came back and allowed the bleeding hearts to give them honor, refuge and attention because many Americans chose to remain silent while the demonstrators received the media attention. Some of those vets were sucked into the communist propaganda and they lost the war at home where it really counts. <br>
 <br><br>
You mentioned the refugees of Nam. &quot;20% of the peasant population were refugees. Were they supposed to feel good about that?&quot; I can tell you there were a lot more homeless refugees then that but they were made homeless by the communist soldier who was dedicated to his trade at any cost. <br>
I remember the villiagers coming, no, running toward us to be medivacked out of their helmets and villages because the communist soldiers were killing anyone and everyone who had not stored any rice for them. <br>
The North Vietnamese soldier we were told had come to their villages with a list of every teacher, mayor, council member and or educated individual in the village and had marked those individuals for assassination. Now, that's genuine environmental damage that was never reported. <br><br>
What is interesting is that during one major operation we discovered 84 tons of good old American polished rice packaged and send to the villagers (the enemy) in VietNam. The burlap bags had been send to them from some Good Samaritan relief organization in Sacramento. Now did they or did nthey not know they were aiding the enemy and thus prolonging the war?. Who were those people? Communist sympathizers and demonstrators that love the freedom they exercise but detest the price others paid for it. <br><br>

